ise, the more proprietary integrated solution is the belle of the ball in m=
any respects? There=E2=80=99s a bit where, yes, being open and modular all =
makes sense, but maybe that=E2=80=99s not going to be good enough for a whi=
le.*

*LS:* I would say it this way. When you look at what the market will look l=
ike five years from now, what I see is a world where you have multiple solu=
tions. I=E2=80=99m not a believer in one-size-fits-all, and from that stand=
point, the beauty of open and modular is that you are able to, I don=E2=80=
=99t want to use the word customize here because they may not all be custom=
, but you are able to tailor.

*Customize in the broad sense.*

*LS:* That=E2=80=99s right.

*Tailor is a good word.*

*LS:* Tailor is the right word =E2=80=94 you are able to tailor the solutio=
ns for different workloads, and my belief is that there=E2=80=99s no one co=
mpany who=E2=80=99s going to come up with every possible solution for every=
 possible workload. So, I think we=E2=80=99re going to get there in differe=
nt ways.

By the way, I am a big believer that these big GPUs that we=E2=80=99re goin=
g to build are going to continue to be the center of the universe for a whi=
le, and yes, you=E2=80=99re going to need the entire network system and ref=
erence system together. The point of what we=E2=80=99re doing is, all of th=
ose pieces are going to be in reference architectures going forward, so I t=
hink architecturally that=E2=80=99s going to be very important.

My only point is, there is no one size that=E2=80=99s going to fit all and =
so the modularity and the openness will allow the ecosystem to innovate in =
the places that they want to innovate. The solution that you want for hyper=
scaler 1 may not be the same as a solution you want for hyperscaler 2, or 3=
.

With this deal AMD isn=E2=80=99t at all giving up on the ecosystem innovati=
ng and evolving; however, the company clearly thinks the various parties in=
volved could use more of a helping hand to figure out all of the various pi=
eces.

AMD=E2=80=99s Integration
-----------------

From AMD=E2=80=99s press release ( https://ir.amd.com/news-events/press-rel=
eases/detail/1211/amd-to-significantly-expand-data-center-ai-systems ) ( em=
phasis mine ):

AMD today announced the signing of a definitive agreement to acquire ZT Sys=
tems, a leading provider of AI infrastructure for the world=E2=80=99s large=
st hyperscale computing companies. The strategic transaction marks the next=
 major step in AMD=E2=80=99s AI strategy to deliver leadership AI training =
and inferencing solutions based on innovating across silicon, software and =
systems. ZT Systems=E2=80=99 extensive experience designing and optimizing =
cloud computing solutions will also help cloud and enterprise customers *si=
gnificantly accelerate* the deployment of AMD-powered AI infrastructure at =
scale=E2=80=A6

=E2=80=9COur acquisition of ZT Systems is the next major step in our long-t=
erm AI strategy to deliver leadership training and inferencing solutions th=
at can be *rapidly deployed* at scale across cloud and enterprise customers=
,=E2=80=9D said AMD Chair and CEO Dr. Lisa Su. =E2=80=9CZT adds world-class=
 systems design and rack-scale solutions expertise that will significantly =
strengthen our data center AI systems and customer enablement capabilities.=
 This acquisition also builds on the investments we have made to accelerate=
 our AI hardware and software roadmaps. Combining our high-performance Inst=
inct AI accelerator, EPYC CPU, and networking product portfolios with ZT Sy=
stems=E2=80=99 industry-leading data center systems expertise will enable A=
MD to deliver end-to-end data center AI infrastructure at scale with our ec=
osystem of OEM and ODM partners.=E2=80=9D

Those references to speed aren=E2=80=99t an accident; right now the fastest=
 way to roll out an at-scale AI solution is to simply buy one from Nvidia, =
at considerable expense and, Su might argue, limited customization to your =
specific needs. Alternatively, you can contract with a company like ZT Syst=
ems or Supermicro to build out your own solution using either Nvidia or AMD=
 chips, but that presents a problem for the former: AMD may come and go as =
far as chip-to-chip comparison with Nvidia goes, but Nvidia is stronger in =
systems and the software ecosystem; being on an equal footing with Nvidia i=
sn=E2=80=99t a good place to be. By acquiring ZT Systems, however, AMD can =
deliver customized solutions for customers much more quickly, helping it ga=
in marketshare in the ongoing AI landgrab.

To put it another way, the model of integration versus modularity can be so=
mewhat simplistic; often the question is where in the value chain you integ=
rate. For example, Apple integrates the operating system with the hardware,=
 using components from the supply chain; a company like Samsung integrates =
the components with the hardware, using the operating system from Google. I=
n this case AMD is integrating with a system designer to maximize its abili=
ty to deliver bespoke solutions rapidly; it may be the case that Nvidia=E2=
=80=99s point of integration with CUDA is more valuable, but that doesn=E2=
=80=99t mean it is the only integration point of value.

What does seem likely is that this continues AMD=E2=80=99s overall trend of=
 primarily serving large hyperscalers. In the case of server CPUs large hyp=
erscalers have the scale to properly value the relative performance gain of=
 AMD CPUs versus Intel ones, and the software capabilities to overcome what=
ever holes in the x86 ecosystem might still exist; in the case of AI, large=
 hyperscalers have the scale and unique needs that require bespoke solution=
s, and, once again, the software capabilities to overcome the CUDA moat. An=
d, to that end, they certainly have the monetary incentive to diversify awa=
y from Nvidia.

This is, interestingly enough, a bit of a blow to Nvidia, in that ZT System=
s designed Nvidia-based solutions for customers like Azure and AWS; ZT Syst=
ems manufacturing arm will still make those systems, but that low-margin bu=
siness is going to be spun out from this deal, and it seems very unlikely t=
hat ZT will be designing any more Nvidia systems. Nvidia, though, may not m=
ind that much: they=E2=80=99d rather design the entire system anyways.

