X7fZLOsOXhDocdScz3LxIPK8G4bAA2Hbxe6T9NGXmZnnDLFzhnFd_gZeA ) I incorrectly i=
mplied that Substack does not have in-app purchases in their iOS app. They =
do, kind of. Specifically, a limited number of publications ( https://suppo=
rt.substack.com/hc/en-us/articles/4571401530132-How-does-paid-subscriptions=
-work-in-the-Substack-app ) do have in-app purchases available, but it=E2=
=80=99s not the default for most publications.

Substack co-founder Hamish McKenzie, meanwhile, wrote a post ( https://supp=
ort.substack.com/hc/en-us/articles/4571401530132-How-does-paid-subscription=
s-work-in-the-Substack-app ) arguing for something similar to what I have b=
een calling for when it comes to creator platforms on the App Store:

But creators aren=E2=80=99t Apple=E2=80=99s traditional customers. They=E2=
=80=99re not app makers or game developers. They don=E2=80=99t actually hav=
e a piece of real estate in the App Store. They instead find their distribu=
tion through media platforms, including the likes of Patreon and Substack. =
It might feel weird for someone who publishes a podcast through Patreon, or=
 a publication through Substack, to receive the same treatment from Apple a=
s Netflix.

McKenzie didn=E2=80=99t go so far as to argue for a specific carve-out for =
creator platforms, but then again, he has a relationship with Apple to prot=
ect. He also =E2=80=94 rightly in opinion =E2=80=94 notes that the friction=
less nature of Apple=E2=80=99s in-app payment solutions very well may mean =
that creators make up some of the percentage they have to give to Apple in =
volume.

Perhaps that points to a middle ground between my proposed solution (Apple =
only takes a share of the creator platform=E2=80=99s revenue) and the curre=
nt state of affairs (Apple takes 30% of every transaction, even though they=
=E2=80=99re not the enabling platform): might Apple just agree to take a sm=
aller percentage of every transaction? Or, alternatively, what if Apple too=
k 30% and then paid a kick-back to the enabling platform for their publishe=
d share (i.e. 10% to Substack)?

To be clear, I think both of these solutions stink =E2=80=94 Apple makes ap=
ps possible, which makes the fees palatable, but Substack makes Substacks p=
ossible, which is why Apple should be charging Substack but not Substackers=
 =E2=80=94 but the current double taxation on creation is even worse and, a=
t the minimum, a bad look for a company that is supposed to care. But they =
probably don=E2=80=99t so it=E2=80=99s a moot point.

